,[309,"Temporary subprocess startup issues"],[89,"That pattern is the center of the library. Every module is designed to fit back into the same `[error, value]` shape."],[27,"That shape is intentionally repetitive. It makes failure handling obvious during code review."],[83,"The fastest way to understand Yieldless is to wire three modules together:"],[374,"The first task failure aborts the group immediately"],[375,"The group waits for every child task to settle before returning"],[128,"The handler body stays linear. There is no framework-specific DSL to learn."],[112,"The main process can use the same tuple style it uses everywhere else."],[116,"The moving parts"],[376,"The original failure is rethrown after cleanup"],[94,"The package ships adapters for common backend boundaries:"],[11,"The principles behind Yieldless and the tradeoffs those principles deliberately make."],[111,"The renderer never depends on Electron's lossy thrown-error conversion."],[274,"The resource wrapper exposes the underlying value as `.value`. That keeps the disposable handle explicit and avoids pretending that current `await using` syntax can destructure directly into a tuple."],[93,"The retry loop respects `AbortSignal`, so if a parent task group is canceled, the pending backoff timer is canceled too."],[305,"The retry loop stops immediately when the parent signal is aborted"],[29,"The schema, router, IPC, and Node modules are adapters. They are not attempts to replace the libraries they sit beside."],[188,"There is no hidden container lookup"],[62,"This page is the short list of habits that keep tuple-based code clean under real production pressure."],[120,"This recipe shows the shape Yieldless is best at: an HTTP request that validates input, performs a few pieces of I/O, retries the flaky part, and returns a normal JSON response."],[25,"This rule keeps the library easy to explain to engineers who did not build the original system."],[26,"Thrown exceptions are still useful for process-l